The 94th [[The Boat Race|Boat Race]] took place on 27 March 1948. Held annually, the Boat Race is a [[Rowing (sport)#Side by side|side-by-side rowing]] race between crews from the Universities of [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] along the [[River Thames]].  In a race umpired by former rower [[Claude Taylor (rower)|Claude Taylor]], Cambridge won by five lengths in a record time of 17 minutes and 50 seconds, beating the existing record set in the [[The Boat Race 1934|1934 race]].  The victory, their second in a row, took the overall record in the race to 50&ndash;43 in Cambridge's favour.

==Background==
[[The Boat Race]] is a [[Rowing (sport)#Side by side|side-by-side rowing]] competition between the [[University of Oxford]] (sometimes referred to as the "Dark Blues")<ref name=blues>{{Cite web | url = http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/apr/06/theobserver | work = [[The Observer]] | title = Dark Blues aim to punch above their weight | date = 6 April 2003 | accessdate = 10 September 2014 }}</ref> and the [[University of Cambridge]] (sometimes referred to as the "Light Blues").<ref name=blues/>  First held in 1829, the race takes place on the {{convert|4.2|mi|km}} [[The Championship Course|Championship Course]] on the [[River Thames]] in southwest London.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/uk/london/10719622/University-Boat-Race-2014-spectators-guide.html | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate = 10 September 2014 | date = 25 March 2014 |title = University Boat Race 2014: spectators' guide | first = Oliver |last =Smith}}</ref>  The rivalry is a major point of honour between the two universities; it is followed throughout the United Kingdom and, as of 2014, broadcast worldwide.<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|title=Former Winnipegger in winning Oxford&ndash;Cambridge Boat Race crew|date=6 April 2014|publisher=CBC News|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/former-winnipegger-in-winning-oxford-cambridge-boat-race-crew-1.2600176|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://theboatraces.org/tv-and-radio | title = TV and radio | publisher = The Boat Race Company Limited | accessdate = 10 September 2014}}</ref>  Cambridge went into the race as reigning champions, having won the [[The Boat Race 1947|1947 race]] by ten lengths, and led overall with 50 victories to Oxford's 43 (excluding the [[The Boat Race 1877|"dead heat" of 1877]]).<ref name=results>{{Cite web | url = http://theboatraces.org/results| publisher =The Boat Race Company Limited | title = Boat Race <U+2013> Results| accessdate = 12 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url= http://theboatraces.org/classic-moments-the-1877-dead-heat | publisher = The Boat Race Company Limited | title = Classic moments <U+2013> the 1877 dead heat | accessdate = 12 July 2014}}</ref>

Oxford's coaches were R. E. Eason (who rowed for the Dark Blues in the [[The Boat Race 1924|1924 race]]), J. H. Page and D. T. Raikes (who represented Oxford in the [[The Boat Race 1920|1920]], [[The Boat Race 1921|1921]] and [[The Boat Race 1922|1922 races]]).  Cambridge were coached by F. E. Hellyer (who rowed for the Light Blues in the [[The Boat Race 1910|1910]] and [[The Boat Race 1911|1911 races]]), [[Kenneth Payne]] (who rowed for Cambridge in the [[The Boat Race 1932|1932]] and [[The Boat Race 1934|1934 races]]), [[Harold Rickett]] (a Light Blue three times between 1930 and 1932) and P. H. Thomas (a four-time Blue between 1902 and 1905).<ref>Burnell, pp. 110&ndash;111</ref>  The umpire for the race was former Cambridge rower [[Claude Taylor (rower)|Claude Taylor]] who had represented the Light Blues in the [[The Boat Race 1901|1901]], [[The Boat Race 1902|1902]] and [[The Boat Race 1903|1903 races]].<ref>Burnell, pp. 49, 67&ndash;68</ref>

The rowing correspondent for ''[[The Manchester Guardian]]'' anticipated a close race: "the prospects of Oxford and Cambridge for this year's University Boat-race on Saturday have now become much more even".<ref>{{Cite news | title = Close Boat-race expected | work = [[The Manchester Guardian]] | date = 25 March 1948 | page = 6 }}</ref>  His counterpart at ''[[The Times]]'' was in agreement: "it really seems that whichever crew gets off best in the first two minutes will probably win the race."<ref>{{Cite news | title = Prospects of a close race | date = 27 March 1948 | page = 4 | issue = 51030}}</ref>

==Crews==
The Oxford crew weighed an average of 12&nbsp;[[Stone (unit)|st]] 9.375&nbsp;[[Pound (mass)|lb]] (80.3&nbsp;kg), {{convert|1.375|lb|kg|2}} per rower more than their opponents.  Cambridge saw three rowers return to the crew with Boat Race experience, including their [[Stroke (rowing)|stroke]] A. P. Mellows.  Oxford's boat also contained three former Blues, J. R. W. Gleave, P. N. Brodie and A. J. R. Purssell, all of whom were making their third appearances.<ref name=burn76>Burnell, p. 76</ref>  Three of the participants were registered as non-British: Oxford's G. C. Fisk and W. W. Woodward, and Cambridge's [[Brian Harrison (Conservative politician)|Brian Harrison]] were all from Australia.<ref>Burnell, p. 39</ref>
