==Race==
[[File:University Boat Race Thames map.svg|right|thumb|[[The Championship Course]] along which the Boat Race is contested]]
Cambridge won the [[coin flipping|toss]] and elected to start from the [[Middlesex]] station, handing the [[Surrey]] side of the river to Oxford.  The race was started at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. by umpire Taylor.<ref name=burn76/>  The Light Blues [[stroke rate|out-rated]] their opponents from the start but soon after their number six, [[Paul Bircher]] "[[Catch a crab|caught a crab]]", allowing Oxford to take a half-length lead which they extended to three-quarters of a length by Craven Steps.<ref name=allrecords>{{Cite news | title = Cambridge break all records | first = G. I. F. |last = Thomson | work = [[The Observer]] | page = 8 | date = 28 March 1948}}</ref>  Despite having stopped to allow Bircher to recover his oar, Cambridge drew level and were over a quarter of a length ahead by the time the crews passed the Mile Post, yet nine seconds off record pace and rowing into a head wind. Cambridge were a length ahead at [[Harrods Furniture Depository]] and drew clear as the boats passed below [[Hammersmith Bridge]].<ref name=recordtime/> 

As the crews passed the HMS ''Stork'' training ship, Cambridge began to draw away and were two lengths ahead by Chiswick Steps.<ref name=recordtime/>  With a strong tailwind along Corney Reach, the Light Blues continued to pull ahead and passed below [[Barnes Railway Bridge]] four lengths ahead, and six seconds ahead of the course record.  Cambridge passed the finishing post five lengths ahead in a time of 17 minutes 50 seconds.  The victory, Cambridge's second in a row, and third in the last four races, took the overall record in the race to 50&ndash;43 in their favour.<ref name=results/>  The special correspondent writing in ''[[The Observer]]'' called it "the maddest Boat Race for years".<ref name=cut>{{Cite news | title = Cambridge cut 13 seconds off race record | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 28 March 1948 | page = 1}}</ref>  ''The Times''{{'s}} rowing correspondent suggested it was "a great triumph for the Cambridge coaches, who so often seem able to produce something out of the bag which has not been apparent in practice."<ref name=recordtime>{{Cite news | title = Cambridge win in record time | work = [[The Times]] | date = 29 March 1948 | page = 6 | issue = 51031}}</ref>  Writing in ''The Manchester Guardian'', the rowing correspondent noted that it was "strange that Cambridge had never shown anything like this form in practice",<ref>{{Cite news | work = [[The Manchester Guardian]] | date = 29 March 1948 | title = Cambridge win in record time | page = 2}}</ref>

